My order came and right away she gave me my check without asking first if I wanted something else like coffee (which I did but the very regular service took away that thought). Always liked Le Pain Quotidien for the concept and freshness of the food. However the prices are outrageous.  I visited this LPQ today and had a sub-par salad comprised of mostly dry arugula with zucchini noodles and Pad Thai seasonings for $12.99, had to pay $3.99 extra for a few slices of chicken on top.  I had a small glass of lemonade ice tea half of which was ice.  No bread, no sides, no coffee or dessert. The tab came to $25 with tax and tip. Even in pricey downtown DC this really gets me.  My other disappointment was the service. Granted, I walked in at the height of the lunch service and the place was busy.  But it's not an excuse for rudeness to customers. The server handed me a menu and came to take my order less than 5 minutes later. I had gotten a phone call and was talking on the phone. She leaned across the table asking what I wanted,  forcing me to put my call on hold, and she clearly was not going to spend more than 2 minutes taking that order. Extremely rude. She brought my food and the bill came 2 minutes after I started eating. I saw that she kept looking over at me to check when I was going to take out my credit card.  Rude again.  Didn't ask if I wanted anything after my salad, coffee or dessert.  At these prices one can and should expect better. I certainly do.  Don't think I'll be back. Le Pain Quotidien is a big corporation and they emphasize profit over quality and service in many locations including this one.
